column4: "tweet": "(12/12) In scientific simulation
column5: you can know the correct output for a given input because you can run your expensive simulation on it."

column4: "tweet": "(11/12) In typical GANs
column5: you can know the correct output for a given input because you know whether the input was an authentic example

column4: "tweet": "(10/12) It seems that adversarial training can be applied whenever you have a way to know the correct answer for an arbitrary input."
"tweet": "(8/12) 3. Then
column5: use the expensive slow simulation on this adversarial inputs to learn its true output. Add this input/output example to the training set for both the emulation and error prediction networks."

column4: "tweet": "(7/12) 2. Then
column5: run the error prediction network in reverse in order to generate an input that is adversarial to emulation network."

column4: "tweet": "(6/12) 1. Alongside the emulator network
column5: train an error prediction network which learns to predict how accurately the emulator will perform on a given input."

column4: "tweet": "(1/12) Expensive scientific simulations can often be significantly accelerated by using input/output examples from the expensive simulation to train a much faster neural network. (See e.g. this impressive result  https://t.co/hqx5XGZ9SB)"
